\begin{abstract}
This note summarizes a simplified search inspired by CMS arXiv:1207.7235: a narrow resonance in diphoton invariant mass (\(H\to\gamma\gamma\)) and a peak in four-lepton mass (\(H\to ZZ\to 4\ell\)).
Background under the signal region is estimated from left and right sideband event densities (events/GeV), averaged and scaled to the signal-region width.
No likelihood fit, systematic uncertainties, or official CMS selections are reproduced.
\end{abstract}

\section{Method}
For each channel we histogram invariant mass \(M\), define a signal region near \(m_H \approx 125\)~GeV, and estimate expected background as
\[
  B_{\mathrm{SR}} = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{N_L}{w_L} + \frac{N_R}{w_R}\right) \cdot w_{\mathrm{SR}}\,,
\]
where \(N_L\) (\(N_R\)) is the event count in the left (right) sideband of width \(w_L\) (\(w_R\)), and \(w_{\mathrm{SR}}\) is the signal-region width.
The naive significance is \((N_{\mathrm{SR}} - B_{\mathrm{SR}})/\sqrt{B_{\mathrm{SR}}}\) when \(B_{\mathrm{SR}}>0\).

